Red Wine Quality Analysis by Payam Gerami

This data set contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

In the following section we explore other variables that have an effect on the quality.

Fixed Acidity

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    4.60    7.10    7.90    8.32    9.20   15.90

Most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile - do not evaporate readily (tartaric acid - g / dm^3).

Volatile Acidity

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1200  0.3900  0.5200  0.5278  0.6400  1.5800

The amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste. As we can see there are some outliers that we can check later to see the quality of the wine with such a high level of acetic acid (acetic acid - g / dm^3).

Citric Acid

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.000   0.090   0.260   0.271   0.420   1.000

Found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines (g / dm^3).

Residual Sugar

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.900   1.900   2.200   2.539   2.600  15.500

The amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet. The maximum amount of sugar we have in our dataset is 15.5 grams but majarity of wines in our sample have between 1 and 4 grams of sugar and the distribution is right skewed (g / dm^3).

Chlorides

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.01200 0.07000 0.07900 0.08747 0.09000 0.61100

The amount of salt in the wine (sodium chloride - g / dm^3).

Free Sulfur Dioxide

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    1.00    7.00   14.00   15.87   21.00   72.00

The free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine (mg / dm^3).

Total Sulfur Dioxide

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    6.00   22.00   38.00   46.47   62.00  289.00

Amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine. As we can see here we have a couple of outliers as well which we can check later to find out the possible effect they have a the quality (mg / dm^3).

Density

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9901  0.9956  0.9968  0.9967  0.9978  1.0037

the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content (g / cm^3).

PH

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   2.740   3.210   3.310   3.311   3.400   4.010

Describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale. The distribution is almost normal and most of the values are in the expected range.

Sulphates

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.3300  0.5500  0.6200  0.6581  0.7300  2.0000

A wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant (potassium sulphate - g / dm3).

Alcohol

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    8.40    9.50   10.20   10.42   11.10   14.90

The percent alcohol content of the wine. Here we might have only one type of wine with too much alcohol in it (% by volume).

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1,599 wines in the dataset with 11 features (fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol ).

Other observations:

  • The quality is an integer number with 6 values.
  • Sugar content distribution is interesting and it shows that most of the wines have between 1 and 4 gram/liter but there are several other wines that have more than 4 grams which is not necessarly a bad thing.
  • As stated in the dataset description, it seems that diffrent types of acid have significant impact on the quality.
  • 75% of the wines have less than 11.10% alcohol

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Based on the dataset description, it appears that the volatile acidity variable has the most impact on the quality

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

residual sugar, alcohol and total sulfur dioxide likely contribute to the quality of a wine.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Since the quality has only 6 values, we categorize this variable into the following factor:

  • < 3 very bad
  • 4 bad
  • 5 average
  • 6 good
  • 7 excelent
  • > 8 very excelent

Bivariate Plots Section

Different types of acids in the wine tend to correlate with each other. Also, quality seems to have a semi strong correlation with alcohol.

The general trend between the volatile.acidity and the quality provides an evidence that as volatile acidity decreases, the quality increases.

And the general trend between the alcohol and the quality provides an evidence that as alcohol increases, the quality increases as well.

And the general trend between residual.sugar and the quality confirms that residual sugar has a minimal impact on the quality of the wine.

The strongest correlation is between fixed.acidity and pH. As it’s clear in the diagram, fixed.acidity decreases when pH decreases.

Bivariate Analysis

Some of the Observed Relationships

We can infer that higher quality wines tend to have high alcohol percentage and low volatile acidity.

Interesting relationships between the other features

It appears that sugar does not have a clear impact on quality.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The relationship between volatile acidity and quality is very strong. The plot clearly shows as the quality goes up, the volatile acidity level decreases.

Multivariate Plots Section

Volatile.acidity and Alcohol seems to be the most important factors affecting the quality of the wine. It looks like wines with less amount of volatile acidity and more amount of alcohol have better quality.

Two other features that have impact on the quality but not as much as alcohol and volatile acidity are sulphates and citric acid. As we can see, when the combination of citric acid and sulphates increases, we tend to have a better quality wine.

Even though pH and fixed.acidity are strongly correlated, there does not seem to be any pattern between the combination of the two and the quality.

Multivariate Analysis

Relationships observed in investigation

The main features of interest are acidity and alcohol.

Interesting or surprising interactions between features?

between other variables and quality, it seems that no clear correlation is available.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This diagram illustrates the correlation between the two most effective features on the quality. Wine seems to have better quality when volatile acidity is between 0.3 and 0.4 g / dm^3, and alcohol is between 11 and 14 percent.

Plot Two

Description Two

Volatile acidity has the strongest correlation with quality. The above boxplot clearly shows the increasing trend in the volatile acidity when wine quality moves from lower level to higher level.

Plot Three

Description Three

Alcohol percentage has the second most strongest correlation with the quality of the wine. It is clear in the above boxplot that high quality wines tend to have higher alcohol percentage.

Reflection

In this analysis I explored the effect of different features of red wine on it’s quality based on the data set that contained 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties. I categorized the quality feature into 6 categories and by exploring the correlation between the features I realized that the most effective features are volatile acidity and alcohol percentage. By looking at combination of other features it’s really hard to find a repeatable pattern and as a result I was not able to find the perfect balance between the features that would result in perfect quality wine.

To expand this analysis, more features could be combined together. There might exists a perfect balance between 5 features together that would result in a perfect quality wine. It is also important to keep in mind that we could categorize the red wines into different types based on characteristics sush as Sweetness, Acidity, Tannin, Fruit and Body then analyse the data to find the perfect balance for each type. This approach most probably would result in better understanding of the features.
